## 3. Technique-by-Technique Breakdown

- Serve
    - Delivers heavy rotation. The firm sponge requires a fine brushing action to maximize spin without accidentally shooting the ball long.

- Receive
    - Push/Stop: Predictable and stable. It doesn't pop up randomly, allowing for aggressive, deep pushes or delicate short stops.
    - Flick: Fast and direct. You can punch through light spin easily.
    - Chiquita/Banana: Very effective. The topsheet grabs the ball well, allowing for strong, arched banana flicks, though with a slightly longer trajectory than D05.

- Loop/Drive
    - First Loop (3rd Ball): Highly trustworthy. It provides the confidence to attack heavy underspin with either speed or extreme rotation.
    - Continuous Looping: Fluid and rhythmic. The balance of speed and spin makes rally-play incredibly stable.
    - Power Loop / Kill: Devastating. On full impact, the ball compresses into the Spring Sponge X and shoots out with highly destructive pace.

- Countering
    - Counter-Topspin: Exceptional. It shines in topspin-to-topspin rallies, maintaining stability and refusing to slip even against high-quality shots.
    - Punch Counter / Active Block: Very crisp. The slightly faster pimple geometry compared to D05 makes punch blocks highly effective.

- Blocking
    - Passive Block: Safe and solid. The ball rebounds cleanly with good depth.
    - Active Block: Lethal. Adding a slight forward press redirects the opponent's energy into a fast, targeted counter.

- Smash & Flat Hit
    - Much better than D05. The No. 180 pimple structure allows for cleaner, faster flat hits and smashes without the spin-sensitivity getting in the way.

- Defense
    - Chop: Possible but difficult. The high speed makes keeping chops low and short a challenge; requires extreme touch.
    - Lob: Outstanding. The elasticity of the sponge makes it easy to return high, deep lobs from far off the table.

